{{BOLD}}Don’t damage the Field.{{/BOLD}} {{ITALIC}}Robot{{/ITALIC}} interactions which damage the {{ITALIC}}Field{{/ITALIC}} or any {{ITALIC}}Field Elements{{/ITALIC}} are prohibited. For the purpose of this rule, “damage” is defined as anything which requires repair in order to begin the next {{ITALIC}}Match{{/ITALIC}}, such as causing part of a {{ITALIC}}Goal{{/ITALIC}} to detach from the {{ITALIC}}Field{{/ITALIC}}. 
{{CALLOUT}}{{ITALIC}}Teams{{/ITALIC}} are responsible for the actions of their {{ITALIC}}Robots{{/ITALIC}} at all times, especially when interacting with the {{ITALIC}}Goals{{/ITALIC}}. If a {{ITALIC}}Team{{/ITALIC}} chooses to repeatedly ram full-speed into a {{ITALIC}}Field Element{{/ITALIC}}, it will be hard to convince a {{ITALIC}}Head Referee{{/ITALIC}} that any damage caused was “accidental.”{{/CALLOUT}}
 Violation Notes: 
{{BOLD}}• {{/BOLD}}In most cases, accidental {{ITALIC}}Field{{/ITALIC}} damage should only be considered a {{ITALIC}}Minor Violation{{/ITALIC}} 
{{BOLD}}• {{/BOLD}}Egregious, intentional, or repeated accidental/{{ITALIC}}Minor Violations{{/ITALIC}} may escalate to a {{ITALIC}}Major Violation{{/ITALIC}} at the {{ITALIC}}Head Referee’s{{/ITALIC}} discretion

{{BOLD}}Don’t Start Before the Timer, and Stop Moving at the end of the Match.{{/BOLD}} {{ITALIC}}Driver{{/ITALIC}} inputs and {{ITALIC}}Robot{{/ITALIC}} may not begin before the {{ITALIC}}Match{{/ITALIC}} timer starts, and must cease at the end of the {{ITALIC}}Match{{/ITALIC}}, when the timer reaches 0:00. 
{{BOLD}}• {{/BOLD}}A pre-programmed routine which causes {{ITALIC}}Robot{{/ITALIC}} motion to start before the {{ITALIC}}Match{{/ITALIC}} or continue after the end of the {{ITALIC}}Match{{/ITALIC}} would violate this rule. 
{{BOLD}}• {{/BOLD}}Any scoring which takes place after the {{ITALIC}}Match{{/ITALIC}} due to {{ITALIC}}Robots{{/ITALIC}} continuing to move will not count toward the score and is a {{ITALIC}}Violation{{/ITALIC}} of this rule. 
{{CALLOUT}}It is expected that many Mix & Match {{ITALIC}}Matches{{/ITALIC}} will have last-second “buzzer-beater” moments. The key moment occurs when the timer display shows 0:00. At many events, a buzzer sound will also play at T=0:00; however, the {{ITALIC}}Field{{/ITALIC}} timer display takes precedence in the event of any audio discrepancies. If a {{ITALIC}}Stack{{/ITALIC}} is released from a {{ITALIC}}Robot{{/ITALIC}} before this moment, it will be allowed to finish its path and the score will be calculated once it comes to rest. However, if it is released after this moment (i.e., the {{ITALIC}}Robot{{/ITALIC}} was still moving past T=0:00) it will not count and the {{ITALIC}}Team{{/ITALIC}} will receive a {{ITALIC}}Violation{{/ITALIC}} as described below. In cases where a last-second scoring attempt is “too close to call,” {{ITALIC}}Teams{{/ITALIC}} will generally be given the “benefit of the doubt” and the score will be counted. {{ITALIC}}Teams{{/ITALIC}} are advised to {{ITALIC}}Place{{/ITALIC}} and release {{ITALIC}}Stacks{{/ITALIC}} a second or two before the timer reaches zero to avoid the need for referee judgment calls.{{/CALLOUT}}
 Violation Notes: 
{{BOLD}}• {{/BOLD}}Because scoring that happens after the {{ITALIC}}Match{{/ITALIC}} is not counted, all {{ITALIC}}Violations{{/ITALIC}} of <GG12> should be recorded as {{ITALIC}}Minor Violations{{/ITALIC}}. 
{{BOLD}}• {{/BOLD}}If a {{ITALIC}}Team{{/ITALIC}} receives three {{ITALIC}}Minor Violations{{/ITALIC}} within the same event, all future <GG12> {{ITALIC}}Violations{{/ITALIC}} at that event will be considered {{ITALIC}}Major Violations{{/ITALIC}} and {{ITALIC}}Disqualifications{{/ITALIC}}. 
{{BOLD}}• {{/BOLD}}This count does not reset for any reason within an event (e.g., Qualification vs Finals Matches{{ITALIC}}, one of the {{ITALIC}}Team’s{{/ITALIC}} “dropped score” {{ITALIC}}Matches{{/ITALIC}}, etc.), but does not include {{ITALIC}}Violations{{/ITALIC}} that occur in {{ITALIC}}Robot Skills Matches{{/ITALIC}} {{/ITALIC}}
{{ITALIC}} 

{{BOLD}}Significant Q&As{{/BOLD}}: 
{{BOLD}}• {{/BOLD}}{{LINK:/VIQRC/2025-2026/QA/2778}}Q&A 2778{{/LINK}} - For Skills, points scored after the Match don’t count, but aren’t a Violation

